Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from a critical tension in modern narrative generation systems: while large language models (LMs) excel at producing fluent and contextually rich text, their full-model inference is computationally expensive, especially for long-form story generation. On the other hand, sparse or filtered inference methods—designed to activate only relevant model components—often degrade output coherence by neglecting global narrative structure. The references provided offer valuable insights: Paper 1 demonstrates how formal grammars can bridge semantic graphs and syntactic derivations; Paper 2 shows that latent hierarchical structures can guide information flow in summarization; and Paper 3 introduces hierarchical conceptual reasoning to improve abstract inference. Building on these, I propose Hierarchical Relevance Gating (HRG), a neuro-symbolic framework that dynamically prunes irrelevant computation paths during inference *based on evolving semantic roles and narrative goals*, while preserving high-level coherence through symbolic narrative planning. Unlike prior work that either focuses purely on attention sparsity or post-hoc filtering, HRG integrates a lightweight symbolic planner that constructs a latent narrative graph (e.g., character arcs, plot milestones) and uses it to modulate neural activation via hierarchical gating. This allows the model to maintain computational efficiency by activating only those layers and neurons semantically aligned with current narrative demands, without sacrificing coherence. The key novelty lies in the bidirectional interaction between symbolic narrative structure and neural inference dynamics—something not addressed in existing sparse inference frameworks.

